WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.315 --> 00:00:01.925
Okay, today we are on the case

2
00:00:01.945 --> 00:00:05.525
of the disappearing website, and it is a strange one.

3
00:00:05.705 --> 00:00:07.285
You have a perfectly good design that

4
00:00:07.285 --> 00:00:09.125
for some users just breaks.

5
00:00:09.615 --> 00:00:12.885
We're talking crucial elements just vanishing into thin air.

6
00:00:13.345 --> 00:00:16.085
So let's put on our detective hats and investigate.

7
00:00:16.735 --> 00:00:18.285
First picture the scene.

8
00:00:18.425 --> 00:00:20.965
You've got this beautiful minimalist website.

9
00:00:21.025 --> 00:00:22.885
You know the kind I'm talking about, clean lines,

10
00:00:22.945 --> 00:00:24.765
subtle shadows, and a color palette

11
00:00:24.765 --> 00:00:26.605
that someone probably spent weeks agonizing over.

12
00:00:26.655 --> 00:00:28.485
Everything is exactly where it should be.

13
00:00:28.585 --> 00:00:33.045
It looks perfect, but then a user somewhere out there flips

14
00:00:33.125 --> 00:00:34.445
a single switch on their computer

15
00:00:34.905 --> 00:00:38.165
and instantly all that perfection, just shatters

16
00:00:38.675 --> 00:00:39.685
buttons disappear,

17
00:00:39.685 --> 00:00:42.045
leaving their text just kind of floating in space.

18
00:00:42.545 --> 00:00:45.405
The clean separate sections of the page all mushed together,

19
00:00:45.865 --> 00:00:48.245
the entire design has completely fallen apart.

20
00:00:48.945 --> 00:00:51.525
So the big question is, where did it all go?

21
00:00:52.085 --> 00:00:53.445
I mean, this isn't a bug in the code,

22
00:00:53.675 --> 00:00:54.885
it's not a server crash.

23
00:00:55.315 --> 00:00:56.765
This is something else entirely.

24
00:00:57.385 --> 00:00:58.565
We need to find the culprit.

25
00:00:58.985 --> 00:01:01.565
And our investigation starts with our prime suspect.

26
00:01:01.955 --> 00:01:05.085
It's a feature, not a bug, called forced colors mode.

27
00:01:05.505 --> 00:01:07.325
And it's the key to this whole mystery.

28
00:01:07.985 --> 00:01:11.005
So forced colors mode, which you might also know as

29
00:01:11.645 --> 00:01:14.805
contrast themes on windows, is an accessibility feature.

30
00:01:15.305 --> 00:01:18.445
It basically lets a user throw out the website's carefully

31
00:01:18.445 --> 00:01:19.525
chosen color scheme

32
00:01:19.745 --> 00:01:22.485
and apply their own high contrast one instead.

33
00:01:23.025 --> 00:01:24.725
So the website isn't actually breaking,

34
00:01:25.155 --> 00:01:28.165
it's being intentionally restyled by the operating system

35
00:01:28.385 --> 00:01:29.605
and for a really important reason.

36
00:01:30.065 --> 00:01:32.085
And before you think, oh, this is just some niche

37
00:01:32.085 --> 00:01:33.245
issue, get this.

38
00:01:33.635 --> 00:01:37.285
Approximately 4% of all Windows users rely on this mode.

39
00:01:37.555 --> 00:01:39.125
That adds up to millions of people

40
00:01:39.185 --> 00:01:41.165
who might be seeing a totally broken version

41
00:01:41.165 --> 00:01:43.325
of your site if it's not built to handle this.

42
00:01:43.865 --> 00:01:45.685
And this feature is an absolute

43
00:01:45.925 --> 00:01:47.285
lifeline for so many people.

44
00:01:47.575 --> 00:01:49.405
We're talking about users with low vision,

45
00:01:49.655 --> 00:01:50.685
light sensitivity,

46
00:01:50.705 --> 00:01:53.445
or conditions that can make reading on a screen really

47
00:01:53.445 --> 00:01:55.605
difficult, even painful for them.

48
00:01:55.615 --> 00:01:58.045
Being able to control the colors isn't just a preference,

49
00:01:58.235 --> 00:01:59.605
it's the only thing that makes the

50
00:01:59.605 --> 00:02:00.605
Web usable.

51
00:02:00.705 --> 00:02:02.085
So how does a feature that's designed

52
00:02:02.085 --> 00:02:04.725
to help people end up making websites totally unusable?

53
00:02:05.035 --> 00:02:06.925
Well, the clue isn't understanding exactly

54
00:02:06.925 --> 00:02:08.685
what the system takes over and more

55
00:02:08.685 --> 00:02:10.165
importantly, what it leaves alone.

56
00:02:11.345 --> 00:02:15.005
Now, this right here is the crucial piece of evidence.

57
00:02:15.305 --> 00:02:18.245
The system takes control of all the colors, backgrounds,

58
00:02:18.435 --> 00:02:20.245
text, border colors, you name it.

59
00:02:20.465 --> 00:02:23.085
But it leaves things like structure your border styles

60
00:02:23.085 --> 00:02:24.685
and images totally alone.

61
00:02:25.105 --> 00:02:28.205
And here's the real smoking gun box shadow.

62
00:02:28.505 --> 00:02:30.285
You know that little drop shadow effect.

63
00:02:30.585 --> 00:02:33.765
It isn't just recolored, the system removes it completely.

64
00:02:34.115 --> 00:02:35.645
That little detail is critical.

65
00:02:36.235 --> 00:02:37.605
Okay, with that knowledge,

66
00:02:37.705 --> 00:02:40.605
we can finally round up our usual suspects.

67
00:02:40.815 --> 00:02:43.285
These are the three most common design patterns

68
00:02:43.285 --> 00:02:45.645
that just completely fail when they're put under the

69
00:02:45.885 --> 00:02:47.045
pressure of forced colors mode.

70
00:02:47.655 --> 00:02:51.285
First up, culprit number one, the borderless button.

71
00:02:52.005 --> 00:02:54.685
I mean, this thing is everywhere in modern design, right?

72
00:02:54.995 --> 00:02:56.485
It's sleek, it's minimal,

73
00:02:56.825 --> 00:02:58.805
and its entire shape is defined only

74
00:02:58.805 --> 00:03:01.045
by its background color. A perfect target.

75
00:03:01.745 --> 00:03:05.525
And here's the fatal flaw. The button's entire boundary.

76
00:03:05.705 --> 00:03:08.485
Its whole shape relies on that background color.

77
00:03:08.905 --> 00:03:11.565
But when forced colors mode changes that background

78
00:03:11.625 --> 00:03:13.005
to match the rest of the page

79
00:03:13.185 --> 00:03:14.805
and there's no border to fall back on,

80
00:03:15.225 --> 00:03:17.205
the button's shape just dissolves.

81
00:03:17.715 --> 00:03:19.045
Poof, it becomes invisible.

82
00:03:19.595 --> 00:03:22.085
Alright, our second culprit is honestly

83
00:03:22.155 --> 00:03:23.245
even more dangerous.

84
00:03:23.485 --> 00:03:25.965
A lot of designers like to replace the default browser focus

85
00:03:25.965 --> 00:03:28.285
outline with a much more subtle box shadow.

86
00:03:28.505 --> 00:03:29.685
And yeah, it looks great,

87
00:03:29.865 --> 00:03:32.765
but it creates a massive, massive accessibility failure.

88
00:03:33.425 --> 00:03:35.045
So let's connect the dots here.

89
00:03:35.585 --> 00:03:37.685
We already know that box shadow gets completely

90
00:03:37.715 --> 00:03:38.725
removed, right?

91
00:03:39.425 --> 00:03:41.405
So by also setting outline, none,

92
00:03:41.785 --> 00:03:44.125
the designer has accidentally removed every

93
00:03:44.485 --> 00:03:45.565
possible focus indicator.

94
00:03:46.205 --> 00:03:48.685
A keyboard user now has absolutely no idea

95
00:03:48.685 --> 00:03:49.845
where they are on the page.

96
00:03:50.225 --> 00:03:52.285
The site is now completely unusable for them.

97
00:03:52.865 --> 00:03:55.805
And our final culprit, the SBG icon,

98
00:03:55.805 --> 00:03:56.965
with a hard coded color.

99
00:03:57.265 --> 00:03:58.965
You know these icons are designed

100
00:03:58.965 --> 00:04:02.645
to be a specific brand blue or maybe an action green.

101
00:04:03.425 --> 00:04:06.485
But here's the problem. When you hard code a fill color like

102
00:04:06.485 --> 00:04:09.325
this forced colors mode, just sees it as another color

103
00:04:09.325 --> 00:04:10.605
that it needs to override.

104
00:04:10.945 --> 00:04:12.965
So what if the user's background is black

105
00:04:13.345 --> 00:04:16.845
and the system overrides this icon's fill to also be black?

106
00:04:17.235 --> 00:04:19.645
Well, poof. The icon is gone.

107
00:04:20.515 --> 00:04:23.165
Okay, so the case seems pretty dire, I know,

108
00:04:23.505 --> 00:04:25.365
but here's the twist in our story.

109
00:04:25.785 --> 00:04:27.845
The solutions to all these problems are actually

110
00:04:27.845 --> 00:04:30.325
surprisingly simple and honestly kind of elegant.

111
00:04:30.795 --> 00:04:32.685
They don't require rewriting everything.

112
00:04:32.685 --> 00:04:34.565
They just require thinking a little differently.

113
00:04:35.175 --> 00:04:37.325
Let's start with our poor borderless button.

114
00:04:37.945 --> 00:04:40.725
The fix is something I like to call the invisible shield.

115
00:04:41.155 --> 00:04:43.645
It's a defense that's completely unseen in normal mode,

116
00:04:43.745 --> 00:04:45.845
but it springs into action the second it's needed.

117
00:04:46.265 --> 00:04:48.085
Here's how this little magic trick works.

118
00:04:48.785 --> 00:04:52.125
You give the button a transparent border in normal

119
00:04:52.195 --> 00:04:53.485
mode, you can't see it, right?

120
00:04:53.625 --> 00:04:55.445
So the design looks exactly the same,

121
00:04:55.825 --> 00:04:57.205
but in force colors mode,

122
00:04:57.425 --> 00:05:00.005
the system overrides the color transparent

123
00:05:00.235 --> 00:05:02.965
with a visible system color while keeping the border

124
00:05:03.025 --> 00:05:04.205
is style and width.

125
00:05:04.745 --> 00:05:06.765
And just like that, the button has a boundary.

126
00:05:06.765 --> 00:05:09.365
Again, it shape is preserved. Problem solved.

127
00:05:09.865 --> 00:05:11.645
So what about our disappearing icon?

128
00:05:12.075 --> 00:05:14.925
Well, the solution here is to turn it into a chameleon.

129
00:05:14.925 --> 00:05:17.325
Something that can adapt to its surroundings instantly.

130
00:05:17.795 --> 00:05:19.365
Instead of a hard-coded color,

131
00:05:19.425 --> 00:05:22.245
we use this special CSS keyword, current color.

132
00:05:22.555 --> 00:05:25.405
It's a really cool value that basically tells the SVG it

133
00:05:26.005 --> 00:05:27.605
whatever the current text color is,

134
00:05:27.675 --> 00:05:29.045
just use that for your fill.

135
00:05:29.375 --> 00:05:32.045
Since the text color is always visible in forced colors

136
00:05:32.155 --> 00:05:34.445
mode, the icon automatically inherits

137
00:05:34.445 --> 00:05:35.645
that same visible color.

138
00:05:36.025 --> 00:05:37.845
It just works. So

139
00:05:37.845 --> 00:05:40.245
after all this detective work, what have we really learned?

140
00:05:40.555 --> 00:05:43.325
Well, it's not just about a few clever CSS tricks.

141
00:05:43.475 --> 00:05:45.085
It's about a fundamental shift in

142
00:05:45.085 --> 00:05:47.245
how we should be thinking about design in the first place.

143
00:05:48.025 --> 00:05:49.965
You see, these aren't just fixes

144
00:05:49.965 --> 00:05:53.085
for some niche accessibility feature using transparent

145
00:05:53.085 --> 00:05:55.765
borders, reliable outlines and adaptive icons.

146
00:05:55.875 --> 00:05:58.165
Make sure design more robust for everyone.

147
00:05:58.555 --> 00:06:00.885
It's about communicating information through structure,

148
00:06:01.265 --> 00:06:03.485
not just through pretty surface level styling.

149
00:06:03.875 --> 00:06:06.165
This is the checklist for a truly resilient,

150
00:06:06.165 --> 00:06:07.405
user-focused design.

151
00:06:07.825 --> 00:06:08.965
And that really leaves us

152
00:06:08.965 --> 00:06:11.525
with one final provocative question to think about.

153
00:06:12.065 --> 00:06:13.885
Is your design built to be beautiful

154
00:06:14.345 --> 00:06:16.005
or is it built to be used?

155
00:06:16.745 --> 00:06:18.525
The very best designs, the ones

156
00:06:18.525 --> 00:06:20.925
that truly solve the case, managed to be both.

157
00:06:21.225 --> 00:06:22.285
Thanks for joining me.
